properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A frontal system will move across the B.C. interior today. Snow is expected to become heavy at times later this morning. Snowfall amounts near 30 cm can be expected by Friday morning. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for overnight and Friday. An intense band of snow associated with the passage of a cold front is expected to move across Far Northern Ontario on Friday. This band of snow may extend from Winisk River to Sachigo Lake early Friday morning and is expected to move southward throughout the day, reaching Lansdowne House to Cat Lake by Friday evening. A total snowfall accumulation up to 10 cm is possible. Hazardous travel conditions are expected due to near zero visibilities in heavy snow and blowing snow. Consider post-poning non essential travel until conditions improve. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall amounts possible in snow squalls on Friday. Total snowfall: Generally 2 to 4 cm, with locally 10 cm or more possible in snow squalls. Time span: early Friday to Friday night. Remarks: A blowing snow advisory is already in effect for poor visibility expected tonight into early Friday. This alert is also in effect due to the possibility of locally heavy accumulations in snow squalls on Friday. Snow squalls will taper to flurries on Friday night. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Northwesterly winds gusting up to 80 km/h are bringing blizzard conditions with near zero visibility in blowing snow to communities in the southern Kivalliq. These blizzard conditions will gradually improve overnight. Overnight, along with the blizzard conditions, temperatures will drop to minus 40 and lower in the southern Kivalliq. These frigid temperatures combined with the gusty northwest winds will give extreme wind chill values of minus 60 to minus 65. These extreme cold values will last through to Sunday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Strongest wind gusts: northwesterly between 60 and 70 km/h. Time span: overnight tonight into Friday. Remarks: Strong winds are expected to develop tonight which will combined with fresh snow to cause reduced visibility in blowing snow. Conditions will be at their worst overnight tonight and during the early morning hours on Friday. Winds will diminish slightly Friday morning, but it is unclear whether widespread blowing snow will continue to be a problem throughout the day due to persistent flurries and snow squalls. Conditions will improve either during the day on Friday, or potentially as late as Friday night as flurries and snow squalls begin to taper off. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
